Given this analysis, my hypothesis is that my opponent is playing a reactive strategy, but with some inertia or delay in adapting to my moves.

* When I play 'scissors', they often play 'paper' (rounds 2, 7, 10, 13, 16, 19, 22).
* When I play 'paper', they often play 'rock' (rounds 5, 8, 11, 14, 17, 20).

This pattern suggests that they might be playing a reactive strategy that tries to counter my previous move. They seem to have a bias towards playing 'paper' when I play 'rock' or 'scissors', and 'rock' when I play 'paper'.
